Rewrite it to strip EVERY `CONTEXT_TAG` value (so `<queue_note>`, `<env>`, and any future kind are covered automatically) plus the existing `<system-reminder>`. Import `CONTEXT_TAG` from `@dorkos/shared/additional-context`:
```ts
import { CONTEXT_TAG } from '@dorkos/shared/additional-context';

/** Strip system-injected tags (system-reminder + every CONTEXT_TAG block) from rendered text. */
export function stripSystemTags(text: string): string {
  let result = text.replace(/<system-reminder>[\s\S]*?<\/system-reminder>/g, '');
  for (const tag of Object.values(CONTEXT_TAG)) {
    const re = new RegExp(`<${tag}>[\\s\\S]*?<\\/${tag}>`, 'g');
    result = result.replace(re, '');
  }
  return result.trim();
}
```
Because `relay_context` is now in `CONTEXT_TAG`, the loop will also strip a `<relay_context>…</relay_context>` block. RECONCILE with the existing `stripRelayContext` (lines 158-165), which is special-cased because the user content follows the closing tag (it returns the content AFTER `</relay_context>`, or null for pure metadata). Keep `stripRelayContext` for the position-sensitive case in the message pipeline (lines ~331-333) where it must return the trailing user content; just ensure `stripSystemTags` (used for inline removal at lines ~313 and ~384) and `stripRelayContext` agree on a single tag name (both ultimately keyed off `CONTEXT_TAG.relay_context`). Document the two-mechanism rationale inline (one strips-in-place, one splits-on-boundary) per the codebase comment-why rule.

